VL  - 4
IS  - 3
SP  - 205
EP  - 237
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/09/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(77)90029-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387877900293
AB  - This paper reports on a micro study of the determinants of technological choice utilizing a sample of observations at the man-machine level from operating plants. The large sample size permits econometric modelling - based on engineering and process analytic principles - of the production relationships involved. It also allows statistical testing of hypotheses. Among the determinants analyzed in the context of differentiated inputs and outputs are policies affecting prices on the factor and product markets. The particular case examined is the choice between imported and locally made looms for cotton textile weaving in Korea. However, methodological concerns are given equal weight in the discussion.
