T1  - The attraction of cities: A review of the migration literature
AU  - Yap, Lorene Y.L.
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 4
IS  - 3
SP  - 239
EP  - 264
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/09/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(77)90030-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438787790030X
AB  - This survey focuses on information relevant to policy concerns about the possibility and desirability of regulating, or accidentally affecting, movement to the cities. Two kinds of empirical work are reviewed: the studies on the determinants of migration, and the empirical material on the migrant experience in urban locations. Unfortunately, the policy implications of the literature are much more tentative than the descriptive aspects -due to data, design, and methodological problems. However, the results suggest that while migration is controllable within limits, conditions in cities exert a strong pull, and that, in spite of large inflows, migrants are being assimilated into the urban economy and are contributing to urban output growth.
